  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT233-kilavi">paṭṭapiṉṟai varaiyātu ceṉṟu viṉaimuṟṟi mīḷun talaimakaṉ tērppākaṟkuc
          colliyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Uttered to the charioteer by HIM who returned after
          completing [his] work, having gone without marrying after it had become [public]. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT233">
          <l> kavalai keṇṭiya vakalvāyc ciṟukuḻi</l>
          <l> koṉṟai yoḷvī tāayc celvar</l>
          <l> poṉpey pēḻai mūytiṟan taṉṉa</l>
          <l> kāretir puṟavi ṉatuvē yuyarntōrkku</l>
          <l> nīroṭu corinta miccil yāvarkkum</l>
          <l> varaikō ḷaṟiyāc coṉṟi</l>
          <l> niraikōṟ kuṟuntoṭi tantai yūrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>The village of the father of [her with] tight<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kuṟum
            toṭi</term>: what may <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟum </term> "short" mean with reference to
            bracelets? It presumably can either refer to their shape ("thin") or to their size
            ("tight"). Since in a parallel passage in KT 267.5 one further attribute possibly means
            "broad", it seems more probable that the meaning is "tight".</note> bracelets in a row<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nirai kōl ... toṭi</term> : the suggestion of taking <term xml:lang="ta">kōl </term> (a fairly unclear standard epithet of bangles) as an
            expression similar to <term xml:lang="ta">nirai</term> , namely as "row" (cf. note on KT
            267.5), is less convincing when both attributes appear in a row. Cām.’s gloss in this
            passage is <term xml:lang="ta">tiraṭciyaiyuṭaiya</term> , "round".</note></l>
          <l>[means] cooked rice that knows no limit</l>
          <l rend="indent">for anyone, as a rest of what is poured forth with water<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nīroṭu corinta miccil</term> : Cām. understands this
            as a rest (= an addition) to the gift given into the hand together with water.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent8">for high-born ones. <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uyarntōrkku</term>
            : Cām. understands "for the erudite ones", but possible is also "for the high-born ones"
            as it is in the poetological idiom. Yet another possibility is that the whole refers to
            a kind of <term xml:lang="sa">śrāddha</term> ceremony, and that the <term xml:lang="ta">uyarntōr</term> are the
            ancestors who receive the offering, while the rest is given as food to the guests.</note></l>
          <l>It [lies] in the woodland, in the face of the rainy season,</l>
          <l rend="indent">as if the lid is opened of the gold-raining baskets</l>
          <l rend="indent6">of prosperous people,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">since the bright blossoms of the Laburnum are spread</l>
          <l rend="indent4">in small pits<note place="foot">So this means the <term xml:lang="ta">
            Koṉṟai</term> flowers have already fallen down = the rainy season is well in progress?</note>
            with wide mouths dug for the Kavalai plants.<note place="foot">Or: "dug on crossroads".</note></l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
